&gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com
&gt; &lt;mailto:archive-crawler%40yahoogroups.com&gt;, Gordon Mohr &lt;gojomo@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; On 4/8/10 1:33 PM, Rajkumar wrote:
&gt;  &gt; &gt; hi,
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Since we are trying to use heritrix 3.0 api in order to invoke
&gt; heritrix (using our http client), is there a way to invoke those api&#39;s
&gt; using HTTP than https.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; i searched for the documentation in order to convert the https to
&gt; http but i am not able to find anything.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Can someone please help on how to achieve this?
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Are you sure you can&#39;t use HTTPS with your HTTP client code? Many HTTP
&gt;  &gt; client utilities have an SSL option.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; We considered, but ultimately did not include in H3, a command-line
&gt;  &gt; switch to listen for plain HTTP rather than HTTPS.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; You could use some combination of other netcat/openssl programs to set
&gt;  &gt; up a proxy that accepts normal HTTP and forwards to HTTPS. For example,
&gt;  &gt; using the &#39;ncat&#39; program that&#39;s part of &#39;nmap&#39;, this one-liner on the
&gt;  &gt; same machine as the crawler sets up such a proxy on port 8008:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; % ncat -l 8008 -c &quot;ncat --ssl localhost 8443&quot;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Be sure to review and understand the &#39;Security Considerations&#39; of the
&gt;  &gt; Heritrix administrative interface:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt; https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/Security+Considerations &lt;https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/Security+Considerations&gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Note especially that if your crawler operator credentials are
&gt;  &gt; compromised by any mechanism (observed in transit over unencrypted link;
&gt;  &gt; failure to verify that SSL connect was with intended server-certificate;
&gt;  &gt; choice of weak login/password; etc.), then resulting unauthorized access
&gt;  &gt; to the crawler interface allows an attacker to change files, and run
&gt;  &gt; arbitrary code, on the crawler machine with the privileges of the user
&gt;  &gt; account used to the launch the Java VM.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; That&#39;s why we recommend:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; - pick strong credentials
&gt;  &gt; - only connect via HTTPS, and verify the expected server certificate
&gt;  &gt; - use additional redundant mechanisms (listening only for local
&gt;  &gt; connections; firewall policies) to prevent connections from unexpected
&gt;  &gt; places
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; - Gordon @ IA
